\begin_layout Subsection
Compounding Intervals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An annual interest rate might be compounded with a smaller interval (loan
 in a bank - paid every month).
 For example, a 8% yearly interest is actually 8.33% if compounded daily.
 The general formula is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FV=P(1+\frac{r}{k})^{kN}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the number of compounding intervals per year, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interest which is compounded (r) is the 
\series bold
annual percentage rate
\series default
 (APR), whle the actual rate is the 
\series bold
effective annual rate
\series default
 (EAR).
 When the number of compounding intervals is infinite, the limit inside
 the parentheses is 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, and the EAR is accordingly calculated.
\end_layout

